WEBVTT

00:04.874 --> 00:07.007
["This Is Not a Love Song"
by Katie Cruel playing]

00:09.096 --> 00:11.141
♪

00:26.722 --> 00:28.680
[breathing heavily]

00:28.724 --> 00:33.642
♪ What did I say?

00:33.685 --> 00:36.079
♪ What did I do?

00:36.123 --> 00:39.952
♪ Lord, I'm a hurricane

00:39.996 --> 00:42.955
♪ Headed for you

00:42.999 --> 00:46.611
♪ Runaway train

00:46.655 --> 00:49.832
♪ Nothing to lose

00:49.875 --> 00:53.618
♪ Boy, I'm a hurricane

00:53.662 --> 00:56.273
♪ Headed for you

00:56.317 --> 00:59.624
♪ Runaway train

00:59.668 --> 01:02.584
♪ Nothing to lose

01:02.627 --> 01:07.371
♪ Boy, I'm a hurricane

01:07.415 --> 01:08.720
♪ Headed

01:08.764 --> 01:12.768
♪ Headed for you.

01:12.811 --> 01:14.813
[Corinne moans]

01:24.562 --> 01:26.869
[knock on door]

01:29.176 --> 01:30.002
[gasps]

01:30.046 --> 01:31.352
Surprise.Weston.

01:31.395 --> 01:32.788
What are you doing here?

01:32.831 --> 01:34.181
Come in. Come in.[grunts]

01:34.224 --> 01:36.008
I thought
you were in South Carolina.

01:36.052 --> 01:37.271
Finished my assignment early.

01:37.314 --> 01:39.664
A week early.It doesn't happen often.

01:39.708 --> 01:41.492
But I had this extra time,
so I figured

01:41.536 --> 01:45.148
why not spend it with you.

01:47.977 --> 01:50.240
I'm surprised you made
it here in this weather.

01:50.284 --> 01:51.633
Oh, my gosh,
tell me about it.

01:51.676 --> 01:53.635
My four-wheel drive
was barely hanging on.

01:53.678 --> 01:56.072
[chuckles]: Nobody
should be on the road right now.

01:56.116 --> 01:57.421
SARAH:Yeah.

01:57.465 --> 01:59.728
Hey, Fenway.Yeah, hopefully,
our plow teams

01:59.771 --> 02:01.599
will make some progress.Sarah,

02:01.643 --> 02:03.427
temperature's dropped, like,
ten degrees in the past hour.

02:03.471 --> 02:04.950
All that wet snow
is freezing over.

02:04.994 --> 02:07.605
Main Street's like the world's
most extreme luge track.

02:07.649 --> 02:09.172
You can't send
plows out there.

02:09.216 --> 02:10.913
I already did. [door opens]

02:10.956 --> 02:13.916
AJ: Oh. I'm shocked
you're still here, Grover.

02:13.959 --> 02:16.353
GROVER: Yeah, Luis asked me to
stay here and watch the roof.

02:16.397 --> 02:18.703
Thank God. I just pulled
a bus out of a snowbank.

02:18.747 --> 02:20.879
But I had to stop.
The roads are all iced up.

02:20.923 --> 02:22.185
It's way too dangerous

02:22.229 --> 02:24.187
to try to get
to Lakeshore.Lakeshore?

02:24.231 --> 02:25.580
[door opens]What were you going

02:25.623 --> 02:27.016
all the way out there for?

02:27.059 --> 02:28.583
It was because of me.GROVER:
Oh.

02:28.626 --> 02:30.062
Bella.

02:30.106 --> 02:32.761
Uh, is it winter break already?[door closes]

02:32.804 --> 02:35.546
Uh, no.
They let me come home early.

02:35.590 --> 02:36.982
I'm gonna take my finals
at home.

02:37.026 --> 02:39.811
Oh. Everything okay?BELLA:
If you call my dad

02:39.855 --> 02:41.422
and Alexis
getting a divorce "okay,"

02:41.465 --> 02:43.206
then yeah. Everything's great.

02:43.250 --> 02:44.686
GROVER:
I thought they were back

02:44.729 --> 02:46.166
in New York.BELLA:
They were.

02:46.209 --> 02:47.993
For couples therapy.

02:48.037 --> 02:50.953
But that didn't work,
obviously, so Alexis is

02:50.996 --> 02:53.956
gonna come back this
weekend to get her things.

02:53.999 --> 02:57.133
So, here I am, seven and a half
hours alone on a bus

02:57.177 --> 02:58.917
to help my dad
pick up the pieces.

02:58.961 --> 03:00.615
You were alone on the bus?BELLA:
Mm-hmm.

03:00.658 --> 03:02.443
Yeah. I guess everyone else
was smart enough

03:02.486 --> 03:04.532
to avoid traveling
during the snow-pocalypse.

03:04.575 --> 03:07.012
Yeah, her dad was supposed to
pick her up from the station,

03:07.056 --> 03:09.058
but his car wouldn't start
in the cold.

03:09.101 --> 03:10.277
Called him, told him
we'd wait it out here

03:10.320 --> 03:11.365
until the worst
of it passed over.

03:11.408 --> 03:12.409
Yeah, of course.

03:12.453 --> 03:13.454
I'll get you home

03:13.497 --> 03:14.890
as soon as the
visibility improves.

03:14.933 --> 03:16.283
Yeah, no rush.

03:16.326 --> 03:19.895
The mess my life just became
isn't going anywhere.

03:19.938 --> 03:22.114
SARAH:
I wish I had

03:22.158 --> 03:25.944
better news, but this blizzard
is much worse than we expected.

03:25.988 --> 03:29.774
With zero visibility
and windchill factor at -25,

03:29.818 --> 03:32.429
I have no choice
but to call in the plow teams

03:32.473 --> 03:34.866
and stop
all snow-clearing efforts.

03:34.910 --> 03:36.738
Anyone who is
still outside,

03:36.781 --> 03:38.479
I need you to find
the nearest shelter

03:38.522 --> 03:41.133
and stay there
until the storm passes.

03:41.177 --> 03:43.571
Like any storm,
we need to be prepared

03:43.614 --> 03:45.573
to lose power and cell service.

03:45.616 --> 03:48.706
If we all stay calm
and stay warm,

03:48.750 --> 03:51.056
we will get through this the way
we get through everything:

03:51.100 --> 03:52.797
together.

03:52.841 --> 03:54.321
♪

03:54.364 --> 03:56.323
[panting]

03:56.366 --> 03:58.760
[lamp buzzing]

04:00.327 --> 04:02.851
[distorted]: We've all seen
our fair share of nor'easters,

04:02.894 --> 04:04.331
but this is not
your average storm.

04:04.374 --> 04:06.681
It looks like we're about
to give the blizzard of '78

04:06.724 --> 04:07.943
a run for its money.

04:07.986 --> 04:10.162
We find ourselves

04:10.206 --> 04:13.905
in the perfect conditions
for disaster.

04:13.949 --> 04:15.907
So stay where you are

04:15.951 --> 04:18.214
and hold your loved ones close.

04:18.258 --> 04:20.390
It's gonna be a long night.

04:25.874 --> 04:26.962
I can't believe we did this.

04:27.005 --> 04:28.442
How could I let
this happen?

04:28.485 --> 04:30.922
I... I think I'm gonna be sick.

04:30.966 --> 04:33.273
Look, just calm down.
It's not that bad.

04:33.316 --> 04:35.884
I'm married, Danny.
Not sleeping with other people

04:35.927 --> 04:37.277
is, like, the one rule
you're not supposed to break.

04:37.320 --> 04:38.582
It isthat bad.

04:38.626 --> 04:41.411
It literally couldn't be worse.

04:42.456 --> 04:44.153
And now it's worse.

04:44.196 --> 04:45.763
[thud][screams]

04:45.807 --> 04:46.634
You okay?

04:46.677 --> 04:48.462
No, I'm not okay!

04:48.505 --> 04:50.594
I am the opposite of okay.
And you asking me

04:50.638 --> 04:53.728
if I am okay
makes me even less okay.

04:53.771 --> 04:56.470
I'm sorry. Look,
can we just talk for a second?No.

04:56.513 --> 04:57.906
I don't want to talk to you.

04:57.949 --> 04:59.342
I don't want to be
in the same room with you.

04:59.386 --> 05:00.952
I don't want to look at you.
I just...

05:00.996 --> 05:04.347
I want to put the nightmare
of this night behind me

05:04.391 --> 05:06.349
and never think of it again.

05:20.537 --> 05:23.018
[footsteps approaching]

05:27.022 --> 05:28.371
Door's blocked.

05:28.415 --> 05:29.241
Blocked by what?

05:29.285 --> 05:30.721
By a family of cave trolls.

05:30.765 --> 05:32.288
By snow, Danny.

05:34.116 --> 05:38.425
So we're trapped in here.
Together.

05:45.606 --> 05:47.999
Quite the library.

05:48.043 --> 05:51.960
You have Faust
in the original German.

05:52.743 --> 05:55.224
Gravity's Rainbow.Ah.

05:55.267 --> 05:58.401
Emma Goldman's autobiography.

06:00.229 --> 06:01.361
I know she's your favorite.

06:01.404 --> 06:02.710
Emma Goldman was

06:02.753 --> 06:06.931
an anti-war, anti-oppression
anarcha-feminist

06:06.975 --> 06:09.717
who defended free speech,
fought for workers' rights,

06:09.760 --> 06:12.241
promoted sexual literacy
for women

06:12.284 --> 06:14.939
and supported
homosexuality

06:14.983 --> 06:17.333
all before the invention
of sliced bread.

06:17.377 --> 06:18.465
Of course she's my favorite.

06:18.508 --> 06:20.031
She should be
everyone's favorite.

06:20.075 --> 06:23.731
[laughs]: This? Okay,
this is my favorite.

06:24.688 --> 06:26.690
Oh. That's from

06:26.734 --> 06:28.562
the Penny Lane Playhouse.

06:28.605 --> 06:31.216
It's been in Greylock
since 1923.

06:31.260 --> 06:34.219
They put on an annual
summer show for kids.

06:34.263 --> 06:37.527
Corinne, Grover, AJ and I,
we all did them every year.

06:37.571 --> 06:39.050
Danny was even in a few.

06:39.094 --> 06:40.835
Titus Andronicus, I assume.

06:40.878 --> 06:43.098
Yeah, that's right before
I eat the pies

06:43.141 --> 06:44.708
with my children's heads
baked into them.

06:44.752 --> 06:47.189
[chuckles]
Nice.

06:49.234 --> 06:51.367
Um...

06:51.411 --> 06:54.065
I think I still have
that bunny costume

06:54.109 --> 06:55.327
somewhere
in my bedroom.

06:55.371 --> 06:56.807
You should
probably go see it.

06:56.851 --> 06:58.592
See what, your bunny costume?

06:59.419 --> 07:00.942
My bedroom.

07:09.864 --> 07:12.214
GROVER:
Boom. Hat trick.

07:12.257 --> 07:13.737
"Hat trick" is a hockey term.

07:13.781 --> 07:15.435
It applies to all sports.

07:15.478 --> 07:18.133
[sighs] Grover, this is not
a sport. This is barely a game.

07:18.176 --> 07:20.091
[sighs]

07:20.135 --> 07:22.616
Fun fact: "hat trick"
actually comes from cricket.

07:22.659 --> 07:24.139
When a batsman took
three wickets

07:24.182 --> 07:27.621
with three consecutive balls,
he was rewarded with a hat.

07:27.664 --> 07:30.014
Mm, okay.
"Batsman" is not a thing.

07:30.058 --> 07:31.886
Uh, "batsman"
is absolutely a thing.

07:31.929 --> 07:34.062
And you are stalling.

07:34.105 --> 07:35.716
[laughs] Is there any way
we can play something

07:35.759 --> 07:37.805
that doesn't smell
quite like pickles?

07:37.848 --> 07:39.371
Oh, I get it.
[tongue clicks]

07:39.415 --> 07:42.853
Intimidated by my hat trick.
I'm in your head, Johnson.

07:42.897 --> 07:44.638
I'm in your...Batsman, my ass.

07:44.681 --> 07:47.118
[both laugh]

07:47.162 --> 07:50.121
GROVER:Yeah, poor kid. I had no
idea Alexis and William

07:50.165 --> 07:51.296
were having problems.

07:51.340 --> 07:53.342
[sighs]
Me, either.

07:53.385 --> 07:55.649
That's life, I guess.

07:55.692 --> 07:58.913
There's no end
to the secrets people keep.

08:04.179 --> 08:05.789
WESTON:
I don't know.

08:05.833 --> 08:07.704
It's not working for me.

08:07.748 --> 08:11.055
No? It's not?

08:11.099 --> 08:12.883
I'm going for, like,

08:12.927 --> 08:15.016
an Abraham Lincoln thing.

08:15.059 --> 08:17.148
Oh. And I preferred Thoreau.

08:17.192 --> 08:18.628
Really?

08:18.672 --> 08:21.065
Well, not many women
can pull off a neck beard. Here.

08:21.109 --> 08:23.851
Own it. Own it. Yeah.

08:23.894 --> 08:26.157
Oh, be still, my heart.

08:26.201 --> 08:29.204
You have Thor-own me
into a tizzy.

08:29.247 --> 08:33.817
Oh, my God, I'm gonna
Thoreau you out of the tub.

08:33.861 --> 08:36.167
[laughs softly]

08:36.211 --> 08:38.866
I'm gonna interview you, okay?

08:40.650 --> 08:43.044
Tell me about South Carolina.

08:46.351 --> 08:49.180
Mm, Palmetto State.

08:50.138 --> 08:51.922
Birthplace of James Brown.

08:51.966 --> 08:54.098
Okay, I mean your assignment.

08:54.142 --> 08:57.232
My assignment. Sorry,
I was distracted by your thighs.

08:57.275 --> 08:59.669
[both chuckle]

08:59.713 --> 09:02.193
Can we talk about something
besides work? Come on.

09:02.237 --> 09:05.588
Um, will you, t-- uh,
tell me about your tattoos?

09:05.632 --> 09:08.722
Uh, this one is obvious.

09:08.765 --> 09:11.725
This one I got after
my first story was published.

09:11.768 --> 09:13.422
Um, and...Mm-hmm.

09:15.206 --> 09:16.512
"They condemn

09:16.556 --> 09:18.688
what they
do not understand."Cicero.

09:19.559 --> 09:20.647
That's right.
Mm.

09:20.690 --> 09:22.692
It's kind of
my-my philosophy

09:22.736 --> 09:24.738
on journalism.

09:24.781 --> 09:26.348
An educated, informed public

09:26.391 --> 09:29.003
is not a luxury
of civilized society, it's a...

09:29.046 --> 09:30.395
It's a prerequisite for one.

09:30.439 --> 09:31.745
Exactly.

09:32.572 --> 09:34.530
Well, that, and neck beards.

09:37.664 --> 09:39.230
I really like you.

09:40.231 --> 09:41.276
What?

09:42.930 --> 09:46.107
This is the only bathtub I want
to be sitting in right now.

09:47.282 --> 09:48.413
But, uh, I mean,

09:48.457 --> 09:50.894
if you want to sit
in other bathtubs,

09:50.938 --> 09:53.636
that's...
that's fine, you know?

09:53.680 --> 09:55.986
I'm not trying to...
[laughs]

09:56.030 --> 09:57.945
chain you to one tub.

10:00.251 --> 10:02.297
I don't need to sit
in any other bathtubs.

10:03.646 --> 10:05.996
This is, this is the only tub
I need.

10:06.040 --> 10:08.869
Okay. Cool.

10:09.696 --> 10:10.740
[chuckles]:
Okay.

10:10.784 --> 10:12.612
Okay.

10:12.655 --> 10:14.657
Mm-hmm.

10:14.701 --> 10:16.267
[chuckles]

10:17.442 --> 10:18.966
Have you been down
in the basement?

10:19.009 --> 10:20.663
I didn't know
t-there was a basement.

10:20.707 --> 10:22.317
Well, there is, and it's packed.

10:22.360 --> 10:24.188
Costumes from Shakespeare
in the park,

10:24.232 --> 10:27.322
musical instruments, props
from the Christmas pageant

10:27.365 --> 10:29.193
and decorations from

10:29.237 --> 10:34.634
every holiday you can think of,
including these.

10:34.677 --> 10:37.854
Batteries are still good.

10:38.855 --> 10:41.858
Absolutely not.
Are you crazy?

10:41.902 --> 10:43.164
I'm just trying
to get us some light.

10:43.207 --> 10:45.470
No, okay, well, then...

10:45.514 --> 10:47.472
I don't know, use...

10:47.516 --> 10:49.518
use these.

10:53.783 --> 10:55.567
Okay, I guess
we'll spend

10:55.611 --> 10:58.396
the evening in the eerie glow
of the undead then.

11:02.313 --> 11:04.098
[groans]

11:04.141 --> 11:06.143
How's there no signal?

11:06.187 --> 11:07.971
Do you have any service?

11:08.015 --> 11:10.582
[exhales]
Cell towers are probably out.

11:10.626 --> 11:14.064
Won't be back online till
after the storm lets up.

11:16.327 --> 11:19.722
You said Josh and Adam are
in Boston all week, right?

11:19.766 --> 11:21.724
Cub Scouts retreat.

11:21.768 --> 11:23.334
I know they're safe.

11:23.378 --> 11:26.511
Adam checked in a few
hours ago, I just, I...

11:28.209 --> 11:30.167
I don't know, it's all
hitting me, you know, it's...

11:30.211 --> 11:31.691
[exhales]
How's Adam

11:31.734 --> 11:33.823
ever gonna look me
in the eye again?

11:35.042 --> 11:37.087
How's Josh?

11:40.787 --> 11:43.441
Yeah, I've been thinking
the same thing about Piper.

11:44.529 --> 11:45.748
I get how you feel.

11:45.792 --> 11:47.532
You have no idea how I feel.

11:47.576 --> 11:48.969
Piper is only your fiancée.

11:49.012 --> 11:50.405
It's completely
different.

11:50.448 --> 11:51.667
It's not completely different.

11:51.711 --> 11:54.409
Yes it is-- fiancées
are disposable.

11:54.452 --> 11:56.280
Trust me, I would know.

12:01.372 --> 12:04.027
Okay, look, this whole thing
is gonna stay between us.

12:04.071 --> 12:06.029
As far as anyone else
is concerned,

12:06.073 --> 12:08.510
we were at the art show;
then you went home,

12:08.553 --> 12:10.033
I went back to my motel.

12:10.077 --> 12:12.993
Wow, if only that were true.

12:14.646 --> 12:16.344
What's taking so long?

12:16.387 --> 12:18.259
WESTON: I'm starting
to regret this idea.

12:18.302 --> 12:21.915
It's not my fault you didn't
bring enough warm clothes.

12:21.958 --> 12:24.221
Are you filming this?
No.

12:24.265 --> 12:26.484
Well...

12:26.528 --> 12:28.225
you should be.

12:29.661 --> 12:31.489
Huh?
[laughs]

12:33.448 --> 12:36.886
[chuckling]:Oh...

12:36.930 --> 12:38.409
I admire your
commitment.

12:38.453 --> 12:41.630
I really admire that commitment.Good.

12:41.673 --> 12:45.112
Yeah, because I took the liberty
of borrowing one of your thongs.

12:45.155 --> 12:47.592
As long as you didn't use
my razor to shave your legs.

12:47.636 --> 12:49.594
Never. I'm a wax man.

12:49.638 --> 12:52.119
[laughs][moaning outside]

12:53.816 --> 12:55.339
What are you doing here?

12:55.383 --> 12:57.385
Look, I know I'm,
like, the last person you want

12:57.428 --> 13:00.475
to see right now, but my car
just slid off the road

13:00.518 --> 13:02.433
over on-on Mapleton.

13:02.477 --> 13:05.349
And your address was
the only one I knew, so...

13:06.524 --> 13:08.396
Okay, well, um...

13:08.439 --> 13:09.614
Yeah, come in.

13:09.658 --> 13:11.703
We will get you thawed out.

13:11.747 --> 13:14.794
Uh, uh, Paul Cooper,
Weston Woods.

13:14.837 --> 13:16.796
Weston, Paul.

13:16.839 --> 13:18.667
I-I'm her father.

13:19.799 --> 13:23.237
Inside? Gloves?Okay. Yeah, hang up
your gloves inside.

13:29.852 --> 13:32.115
Yeah, from, um...

13:32.159 --> 13:34.814
from where I stand, I could,
I could swear you're sleeping

13:34.857 --> 13:37.207
with the guy who wrote that
really unflattering article

13:37.251 --> 13:38.861
about you
in the national magazine.

13:38.905 --> 13:40.558
From where I stand,
it's none of your business.

13:40.602 --> 13:41.864
Please tell me
you're not that naive.

13:41.908 --> 13:42.996
You can't trust him.

13:43.039 --> 13:44.171
You don't even know him.

13:44.214 --> 13:45.563
I know he's a reporter.

13:45.607 --> 13:47.914
Which means he's here
for one reason-- a story.

13:47.957 --> 13:49.176
I'm not sure that
you're the person I would

13:49.219 --> 13:50.438
look to for a lecture on trust.

13:50.481 --> 13:52.179
I'm just trying
to be protective.

13:52.222 --> 13:53.789
That's what fathers do.

13:53.833 --> 13:55.878
Is it? I actually wouldn't know.

13:55.922 --> 13:58.054
He's a liability.For you,

13:58.098 --> 14:00.056
he's a liability, not for me.

14:00.100 --> 14:02.537
I'm not a wanted criminal.

14:03.581 --> 14:05.757
I didn't steal a bunch
of American state secrets

14:05.801 --> 14:07.411
and leak them online.

14:07.455 --> 14:09.065
I'm not hiding out in Greylock

14:09.109 --> 14:11.024
because it's
a non-extradition country.

14:11.067 --> 14:12.895
Fine, yes.

14:12.939 --> 14:14.941
I-I would...

14:14.984 --> 14:17.291
rather not reveal my location,

14:17.334 --> 14:19.510
or the details
of my life,

14:19.554 --> 14:22.687
to a reporter, which is why
I'm not sleeping with one.

14:24.776 --> 14:26.866
Weston is not that person.

14:26.909 --> 14:29.346
We didn't even start dating
until after he published

14:29.390 --> 14:31.044
his article.Reporters never clock out.

14:31.087 --> 14:32.697
It's a trait of the breed.

14:32.741 --> 14:34.308
You're taking
a huge risk here.

14:34.351 --> 14:35.875
I hope I'm not interrupting.

14:35.918 --> 14:37.441
No. No, not at all.

14:37.485 --> 14:38.834
Guacamole?

14:38.878 --> 14:40.401
Yeah.

14:41.184 --> 14:42.838
[knocking]

14:42.882 --> 14:45.275
Listen, um...

14:46.668 --> 14:47.974
I'm really sorry

14:48.017 --> 14:50.498
about everything that's
going on with your family.

14:51.629 --> 14:54.806
You know, divorce,
divorce can be...

14:54.850 --> 14:56.112
Divorce is divorce.

14:56.156 --> 14:58.114
Exactly.

14:58.158 --> 15:00.029
And, um...

15:00.073 --> 15:01.857
well, you know, it...

15:01.901 --> 15:03.772
Sucks.

15:03.815 --> 15:05.165
Yes.
Yeah.

15:07.036 --> 15:08.864
As do I,

15:08.908 --> 15:11.649
at giving pep talks, apparently.

15:13.086 --> 15:15.827
Look, I'm gonna be fine,
okay?

15:15.871 --> 15:18.352
It's not my first rodeo.

15:18.395 --> 15:20.920
My mom took off with some
other guy when I was four,

15:20.963 --> 15:23.705
so "divorce" was kind of
an early...

15:23.748 --> 15:26.012
vocabulary word
in the Whitmore house.

15:26.055 --> 15:29.493
That must've... been hard.

15:29.537 --> 15:31.582
Yeah.

15:34.846 --> 15:37.240
But then my dad met Alexis.

15:39.068 --> 15:41.027
And she's been
in the picture longer than

15:41.070 --> 15:44.030
my biological mom
ever was, so...

15:44.073 --> 15:45.988
I just...

15:46.032 --> 15:47.990
kind of thought...

15:48.034 --> 15:49.513
I thought

15:49.557 --> 15:52.603
she was different, you know?

15:52.647 --> 15:54.910
♪

15:54.954 --> 15:57.217
[crying]

15:57.260 --> 16:01.438
♪ Of this distant memory...

16:01.482 --> 16:04.050
Bella...Grover, I have to study.

16:04.093 --> 16:05.225
[sniffling]

16:05.268 --> 16:07.140
♪ Get up and go

16:07.183 --> 16:10.752
♪ There's no time to kill.

16:13.276 --> 16:16.584
[ball thumping loudly]

16:21.284 --> 16:23.417
Do you mind?

16:23.460 --> 16:25.245
Maybe if you'd talk to me.

16:25.288 --> 16:28.683
If I do, will you stop
throwing the ball?!

16:30.467 --> 16:33.731
What, you carry that around
in case a yuppy duel breaks out?

16:33.775 --> 16:37.039
Pistols at dawn,
racquets at brunch.

16:37.083 --> 16:38.823
It doubles as a stress reliever.

16:43.524 --> 16:46.266
I didn't even know
you played racquetball.

16:46.309 --> 16:48.877
I picked it up
in New York.

16:48.920 --> 16:50.313
It's really good for you.

16:50.357 --> 16:52.272
Hmm, seems like a lot of things

16:52.315 --> 16:54.100
about New York were
good for you.

16:54.143 --> 16:56.450
Not at first.

16:56.493 --> 16:59.105
I was scared, broke,

16:59.148 --> 17:01.107
couldn't figure out the subway.

17:01.150 --> 17:03.979
I was all alone.

17:04.023 --> 17:06.808
But I was also free.

17:06.851 --> 17:10.899
Being away from my mom
and all her baggage...

17:10.942 --> 17:13.162
was instant relief.

17:14.859 --> 17:16.426
And then after a while...

17:16.470 --> 17:18.472
I was less scared.

17:19.516 --> 17:21.953
Less broke.Less alone?

17:21.997 --> 17:24.304
Eventually I met Piper.

17:24.347 --> 17:25.653
Yeah, and lived
happily ever after. I'm glad

17:25.696 --> 17:27.089
it all worked out
for you, Danny.

17:31.137 --> 17:33.748
So, Paul, what brings you
to Greylock?

17:33.791 --> 17:36.490
What do you mean?

17:36.533 --> 17:37.882
Oh, here we go.

17:37.926 --> 17:39.058
I was...

17:39.101 --> 17:40.581
wondering...

17:40.624 --> 17:43.236
My kids live here.

17:43.279 --> 17:44.672
[laughs]

17:44.715 --> 17:46.108
What brings you to town?

17:46.152 --> 17:47.936
Sarah does.

17:47.979 --> 17:49.764
So another
interview?

17:49.807 --> 17:51.722
No, just-just a visit.

17:51.766 --> 17:54.377
What does your magazine
make of that?

17:54.421 --> 17:57.163
Oh, I'm here on my own time.
It's none of their business.

17:57.206 --> 17:59.469
I would think it would be
exactly their business, huh?

17:59.513 --> 18:01.993
I mean, you wrote
the big article on Sarah.

18:02.037 --> 18:05.127
Wouldn't... wouldn't they
naturally want a follow-up?

18:05.171 --> 18:07.216
Well...

18:07.260 --> 18:08.957
No, what the magazine
publishes and why

18:09.000 --> 18:10.480
is really above my pay grade.

18:14.745 --> 18:17.096
What did they say
about you coming here?

18:17.139 --> 18:19.663
Uh, they didn't say anything.

18:19.707 --> 18:23.189
You were in South Carolina doing
an article about the governor.

18:23.232 --> 18:24.755
Uh-huh.
Right?

18:24.799 --> 18:26.844
The magazine wasn't mad
that you left early?

18:26.888 --> 18:29.891
They were fine with it.
[chuckles]

18:31.327 --> 18:32.720
Who wants more wine?

18:32.763 --> 18:34.678
Yeah, it's not
bad, right?

18:34.722 --> 18:37.464
It's not bad.
It's not bad.

18:39.466 --> 18:41.511
[footsteps approaching]

18:46.125 --> 18:48.692
You're really gonna
sleep in the stairwell?

18:48.736 --> 18:52.131
Not if you stand there
watching me the whole time.

19:06.362 --> 19:10.192
I wasn't trying to say that
things were better without you.

19:10.236 --> 19:13.152
Or that leaving you was easy.

19:14.588 --> 19:16.851
I know.

19:18.374 --> 19:22.639
♪ It's gonna be just fine

19:22.683 --> 19:24.728
♪ Got to hold on to my hand...

19:24.772 --> 19:26.556
Listening
to you just

19:26.600 --> 19:30.473
reminded me of the days
right after you left.

19:31.866 --> 19:35.043
It all came back to me.

19:35.086 --> 19:38.089
While you were in New York
finding yourself,

19:38.133 --> 19:40.222
I was here,

19:40.266 --> 19:43.443
having... panic attacks

19:43.486 --> 19:47.186
and missing the prom and...

19:47.229 --> 19:49.144
I'm sorry about that, too.

19:49.188 --> 19:51.538
They were my demons.

19:51.581 --> 19:53.931
It was my battle,
but you were...

19:53.975 --> 19:55.716
the casualty.

19:55.759 --> 19:59.241
Shouldn't have done it
like that.

19:59.285 --> 20:01.548
Hurt you the way I did.

20:01.591 --> 20:03.245
If I could do it over again...

20:03.289 --> 20:04.812
Yeah, but you can't, Danny.

20:05.813 --> 20:07.684
It's in the past, so unless...
[sniffles]

20:07.728 --> 20:10.383
you found a time machine
under all that weird crap

20:10.426 --> 20:13.081
in the basement, there's
nothing you can do to change it.

20:26.660 --> 20:29.097
I'm sorry about
my attempt

20:29.140 --> 20:31.447
at Divorce 101.
[chuckles]

20:31.491 --> 20:34.145
I should've
stayed in my lane.

20:34.189 --> 20:37.888
You don't need me making your
life harder than it already is.

20:37.932 --> 20:40.630
Oh, you didn't make
my life harder, Grover.

20:40.674 --> 20:42.763
Alexis did.

20:44.939 --> 20:47.028
Have you thought
about maybe

20:47.071 --> 20:49.291
talking to Alexis
about all this?

20:49.335 --> 20:50.727
Alexis doesn't care
about me any more

20:50.771 --> 20:52.468
than she cares about my dad.

20:52.512 --> 20:55.123
Which is not at all.

20:55.166 --> 20:57.604
By this time next week,
she'll probably be

20:57.647 --> 20:59.780
on a beach somewhere,
with her new girlfriend.

21:01.564 --> 21:02.565
Her new girlfriend?

21:02.609 --> 21:04.741
Yeah. Alexis cheated on him.

21:04.785 --> 21:07.004
So if she really
cared about us,

21:07.048 --> 21:10.138
then why would she have
an affair in the first place?

21:13.837 --> 21:15.404
[clears throat]

21:22.324 --> 21:24.500
[clicking]

21:26.459 --> 21:28.591
[crackles softly]

21:28.635 --> 21:31.899
["Relocate" by Kauf playing]

21:38.949 --> 21:40.995
♪

21:48.307 --> 21:50.309
[music playing loudly]

21:50.352 --> 21:52.615
♪

22:02.408 --> 22:04.671
[clears throat]

22:05.889 --> 22:07.108
How do I look?

22:07.151 --> 22:09.197
Dickensian.

22:09.240 --> 22:11.025
[laughs]

22:11.068 --> 22:13.593
Yeah, the Shakespeare stuff
was too small.

22:14.550 --> 22:15.986
What is this?

22:17.423 --> 22:19.120
A dance floor.

22:19.990 --> 22:25.735
♪ Do you feel any better now?

22:25.779 --> 22:27.650
For you.

22:27.694 --> 22:29.783
You can't go to prom
without a dress, can you?

22:29.826 --> 22:33.482
♪ I'm trying to follow
what you told me... ♪

22:33.526 --> 22:35.005
Danny, I-I don't think
it's a good idea. I...

22:35.049 --> 22:38.357
Prom should've been one
of the best nights of your life.

22:38.400 --> 22:41.577
And I took that away from you.

22:41.621 --> 22:43.318
We don't have a time machine.

22:43.362 --> 22:45.842
[laughs softly]
But...

22:45.886 --> 22:47.583
we do have time.

22:48.976 --> 22:50.107
Please, Corinne.

22:50.151 --> 22:52.371
Will you go to prom with me?

23:08.474 --> 23:10.476
You all right?

23:10.519 --> 23:13.348
I'm fine.

23:13.392 --> 23:15.306
I-I just feel bad for Bella.

23:15.350 --> 23:18.353
Divorce is bad enough
without your stepmom

23:18.397 --> 23:19.485
running off with some...

23:19.528 --> 23:20.660
Easy.
You don't even know

23:20.703 --> 23:23.576
what happened,
and neither does Bella.

23:23.619 --> 23:25.447
She doesn't even know
who the other woman is.

23:25.491 --> 23:26.709
Yeah, I wonder if William does.

23:26.753 --> 23:28.276
No, I doubt it.

23:28.319 --> 23:30.974
He is not one to stay quiet
when he's pissed.

23:31.018 --> 23:32.367
If he knew,
he would have been

23:32.411 --> 23:33.977
ranting about it to somebody.

23:34.021 --> 23:35.152
My guess is

23:35.196 --> 23:37.894
Alexis is trying
to protect her partner.

23:37.938 --> 23:39.243
William is her partner.

23:39.287 --> 23:41.550
He's who Alexis
should be protecting.

23:41.594 --> 23:43.509
This other woman is a...

23:45.859 --> 23:47.426
I don't understand why Alexis

23:47.469 --> 23:48.992
would be
protecting her.

23:49.036 --> 23:50.864
Probably because of how
something like this

23:50.907 --> 23:52.692
could damage her reputation.

23:53.693 --> 23:55.216
As a policewoman.

23:55.259 --> 23:58.872
And a newly elected member
of the town council.

24:02.223 --> 24:03.877
No.

24:05.835 --> 24:07.968
Oh, my God. I had no idea.

24:08.882 --> 24:11.014
Wait, you're not,
you're not still...

24:11.058 --> 24:14.931
No. No, it's... no, it's over.

24:14.975 --> 24:17.543
Just one more relationship
I managed to destroy.

24:17.586 --> 24:19.196
Two more, AJ.
You know I love you

24:19.240 --> 24:20.981
and I always got your back,
but I'm not gonna stand here

24:21.024 --> 24:22.678
and tell you that it's okay
that you were sleeping

24:22.722 --> 24:24.158
with a married woman.

24:24.201 --> 24:26.726
The Whitmores are getting
a divorce because of you.

24:26.769 --> 24:28.597
Oh, hold on.

24:28.641 --> 24:29.903
The Whitmores
are getting a divorce

24:29.946 --> 24:31.339
because of the Whitmores.

24:31.382 --> 24:32.862
That marriage was doomed
long before I came along.

24:32.906 --> 24:34.298
Mm, so you don't,
you don't feel guilty?

24:34.342 --> 24:37.388
No, of course I feel guilty.
What I did...

24:37.432 --> 24:39.086
Look, you ask me,

24:39.129 --> 24:41.915
Alexis and William's marriage
isn't the real casualty here.

24:41.958 --> 24:44.526
Bella sitting out there thinking
her stepmom doesn't

24:44.570 --> 24:45.527
care about her is.

24:45.571 --> 24:46.572
The scenario she has

24:46.615 --> 24:48.225
in her head is wrong, Grover.

24:48.269 --> 24:51.881
AJ, you've already crossed
a serious line with this family.

24:51.925 --> 24:53.883
The last thing they need you
to do is to cross another one.

24:53.927 --> 24:57.060
They need to work on
this on their own.

24:57.104 --> 25:00.847
You want to help Bella?
Stay out of it.

25:08.028 --> 25:10.073
♪

25:12.293 --> 25:13.555
[laughs softly]

25:15.992 --> 25:17.603
[grunts softly]

25:22.477 --> 25:26.612
♪ Do you feel any better now?

25:26.655 --> 25:28.004
Hi.
[laughs]

25:28.048 --> 25:30.441
Hi.

25:30.485 --> 25:32.574
[chuckles]
Wow.

25:32.618 --> 25:34.576
♪ Do you feel

25:34.620 --> 25:36.186
You look beautiful.

25:36.230 --> 25:37.623
♪ Any better now?

25:37.666 --> 25:39.581
[clears throat]
Your, uh...

25:39.625 --> 25:41.104
[gasps]...corsage, madam.

25:41.148 --> 25:42.497
W-Where did you get this?

25:42.541 --> 25:45.326
I repurposed it
from a Christmas wreath.

25:45.369 --> 25:46.762
[laughs softly]

25:48.068 --> 25:49.635
Shall we?

25:51.419 --> 25:53.682
♪ A little lost

25:53.726 --> 25:56.163
♪ Colony from the start

25:57.164 --> 25:58.861
Thank you for doing this.

26:00.646 --> 26:02.517
It's perfect.

26:04.737 --> 26:07.783
♪ I can't forget the skin
pulled tight ♪

26:07.827 --> 26:10.307
♪ Every letter read

26:10.351 --> 26:11.874
♪ Is it your justice...

26:11.918 --> 26:13.746
WESTON:
Your dad take Fenway out

26:13.789 --> 26:15.661
to make some yellow snow?

26:20.100 --> 26:22.232
Are you lying about
why you're here?

26:23.582 --> 26:24.713
What?

26:24.757 --> 26:26.759
You are.
I can see it on your face.

26:26.802 --> 26:28.325
Okay, wait a second. Wait...You're just using me

26:28.369 --> 26:29.805
to get another story
for the Yorkshire.

26:29.849 --> 26:31.807
Sarah.It was weird enough,

26:31.851 --> 26:33.330
you showing up a week early.

26:33.374 --> 26:35.419
And then you're dodging
questions about your assignment.

26:35.463 --> 26:36.986
In the bathtub,

26:37.030 --> 26:38.814
you went blank when I asked
you about South Carolina.

26:38.858 --> 26:40.555
It's not what it looks like.

26:40.599 --> 26:42.035
It looks like you're a liar.

26:42.078 --> 26:43.514
I'm not using you for a story.

26:43.558 --> 26:45.212
From the moment
you arrived,

26:45.255 --> 26:47.475
you have been trying
to weasel your way into my life.

26:47.518 --> 26:48.650
Because I like you.

26:48.694 --> 26:50.086
Of course you do.
I sell magazines.

26:50.130 --> 26:52.175
That is not fair.Doesn't make it untrue.

26:52.219 --> 26:54.917
So tell me, what was
the angle for this one?

26:54.961 --> 26:56.310
Were you gonna publish
a tell-all

26:56.353 --> 26:57.616
about what I'm like in bed?

26:57.659 --> 26:58.878
Is that really
what you think of me?

26:58.921 --> 27:00.183
Is that really what
you think of me?

27:00.227 --> 27:01.663
Can we just calm down
for a second?

27:01.707 --> 27:03.012
Did you even go
to South Carolina?

27:03.056 --> 27:04.840
Yes, I went to South Carolina.For a story?

27:04.884 --> 27:05.972
For you.

27:06.015 --> 27:07.321
What is there in South Carolina

27:07.364 --> 27:08.583
that I could possibly want?

27:08.627 --> 27:10.890
Emma Goldman's desk.
What?

27:10.933 --> 27:12.587
There's an antique dealer
in Charleston

27:12.631 --> 27:14.458
who has the desk
she used in 1906

27:14.502 --> 27:16.156
when she was editor of
Mother Earthmagazine.

27:16.199 --> 27:17.679
It was supposed to be
auctioned off tomorrow,

27:17.723 --> 27:19.159
which is why I told you

27:19.202 --> 27:21.509
I'd be in South Carolina
this week.

27:21.552 --> 27:23.990
And then, two days ago,
dealer calls and says

27:24.033 --> 27:25.731
the owner will sell me
the desk directly

27:25.774 --> 27:27.950
if I drive down right now,
so I did.

27:27.994 --> 27:29.560
And then suddenly
I'm back in New York

27:29.604 --> 27:31.867
with a whole week
I didn't think I'd have, so...

27:31.911 --> 27:33.913
so I came up here.

27:35.436 --> 27:37.307
[sighs]

27:38.308 --> 27:39.570
You inspire so
many people,

27:39.614 --> 27:40.963
I figured you should
have something

27:41.007 --> 27:42.617
from the woman who inspires you.

27:45.185 --> 27:47.927
I wanted to surprise
you for Christmas.

27:49.755 --> 27:51.670
[sighs]

28:13.300 --> 28:15.868
Bye-bye. See you never.

28:15.911 --> 28:17.608
What are you doing?

28:17.652 --> 28:20.742
I'm deleting pictures
of Alexis and me.

28:20.786 --> 28:24.137
It's freeing up a lot
of space on my phone.

28:25.791 --> 28:28.445
Bella, you know...

28:28.489 --> 28:33.059
um, I spent a lot of time
with your stepmom in the choir,

28:33.102 --> 28:35.235
and she was always
talking about you.

28:35.278 --> 28:37.106
That doesn't mean much
if she's doing it

28:37.150 --> 28:38.891
out of both sides of her mouth.

28:38.934 --> 28:40.457
I know you're important to her.

28:40.501 --> 28:42.982
Not as important as
her new girlfriend, apparently.

28:44.505 --> 28:46.986
I guess I shouldn't
be surprised

28:47.029 --> 28:49.205
that she left.

28:50.990 --> 28:53.949
My own mom didn't want me.

28:53.993 --> 28:56.778
And now

28:56.822 --> 28:58.998
Alexis doesn't want me.

28:59.041 --> 29:01.130
Alexis does want you, Bella.

29:01.174 --> 29:04.699
She loves you
with all her heart.

29:05.526 --> 29:07.615
When you started playing tennis,

29:07.658 --> 29:10.444
she studied the official
rule book for, like, a month

29:10.487 --> 29:13.186
just so she would know
when to cheer for you.

29:13.229 --> 29:16.145
When you got arrested
at the border protest,

29:16.189 --> 29:17.494
she drove her car

29:17.538 --> 29:19.975
up on the sidewalk
on Finch Street

29:20.019 --> 29:22.804
just so she could
get to you faster.

29:22.848 --> 29:24.850
She came into the station
with a mangled muffler,

29:24.893 --> 29:27.156
but she didn't care.

29:27.200 --> 29:30.029
As long as you were okay.

29:31.770 --> 29:33.989
And when William bought her
that locket last year,

29:34.033 --> 29:36.557
she put your photo inside
instead of his.

29:36.600 --> 29:38.820
You are her greatest joy, Bella.

29:44.260 --> 29:45.392
[exhales]

29:45.435 --> 29:46.567
Hey, uh,

29:46.610 --> 29:48.482
why do you know that?

29:50.136 --> 29:51.267
What?

29:51.311 --> 29:54.618
That thing about
Alexis's locket.

29:55.837 --> 29:57.839
That was
supposed to be

29:57.883 --> 30:00.189
our little secret.

30:01.756 --> 30:04.715
My dad doesn't even know
the photo's not of him.

30:07.631 --> 30:09.372
Oh, my God.

30:13.812 --> 30:16.858
It's you, AJ?

30:16.902 --> 30:19.034
You're the one Alexis
has been sleeping with?

30:19.078 --> 30:20.166
Bella...

30:20.209 --> 30:21.950
Oh, my God.

30:21.994 --> 30:25.388
What... Why would you--
why would you do that?

30:25.432 --> 30:26.868
Bella...

30:26.912 --> 30:29.088
Bella, just wait. Bella...No, no. No, no, no.

30:29.131 --> 30:33.135
Please, please-please just--
please just stay away from me.

30:33.179 --> 30:33.832
[crying]

30:41.709 --> 30:43.493
I know you don't want to see me,

30:43.537 --> 30:46.322
but we're stuck
here, okay?

30:46.366 --> 30:47.541
We might as well talk.

30:47.584 --> 30:50.457
I don't want to talk to you.

30:53.764 --> 30:56.680
Things between me
and Alexis are over.

30:58.160 --> 30:59.901
I swear to you.
I'm sorry.

30:59.945 --> 31:03.209
I don't care if you're sorry.
I don't forgive you.

31:06.386 --> 31:08.344
♪ If you're...

31:08.388 --> 31:11.608
This is not about
my conscience, but...

31:11.652 --> 31:13.262
if it's forgiveness I'm after,

31:13.306 --> 31:15.612
I'll seek it with God,
not a teenager.

31:15.656 --> 31:20.269
Look, I've made more mistakes
than I can count, Bella.

31:21.227 --> 31:23.359
And none worse than this.

31:23.403 --> 31:24.795
I wouldn't blame you
if you wanted

31:24.839 --> 31:26.928
to run me over with
a pickup truck tomorrow.

31:26.972 --> 31:31.193
But you need to know,
everything I said about

31:31.237 --> 31:34.414
Alexis's feelings for you
is true.

31:34.457 --> 31:36.329
♪ Like you're told...

31:36.372 --> 31:40.202
She loves you.
She's so proud of you.

31:40.246 --> 31:42.901
She's so proud to be
your stepmother.

31:46.382 --> 31:47.731
You can hate me,

31:47.775 --> 31:51.518
you can hate her, but just...

31:53.607 --> 31:55.565
...know you're loved, Bella.

31:57.480 --> 32:00.440
And nothing's ever
gonna change that.

32:11.103 --> 32:13.409
[door closes]

32:14.410 --> 32:15.846
PAUL:
Good boy.

32:15.890 --> 32:17.370
Good boy.

32:17.413 --> 32:19.241
I'm hungry again.
[chuckles]

32:21.417 --> 32:24.072
[shivers]

32:24.116 --> 32:26.466
Where's Weston?

32:26.509 --> 32:28.685
Upstairs.

32:32.167 --> 32:33.473
Something happen?

32:33.516 --> 32:35.083
Yeah, you.

32:35.127 --> 32:37.825
What's that supposed to mean?

32:37.868 --> 32:41.698
He was in South Carolina, um,
to get me a present.

32:41.742 --> 32:43.744
It was gonna be a surprise.

32:43.787 --> 32:45.485
That's why
he was cagey earlier,

32:45.528 --> 32:47.748
not because he was
hunting some...

32:47.791 --> 32:50.533
some tabloid scoop on me,
or chasing

32:50.577 --> 32:52.274
some dark secret of yours.

32:52.318 --> 32:53.580
He was just trying
to do something nice.

32:53.623 --> 32:55.756
He was trying to do
something nice.

32:55.799 --> 32:57.062
And I tore his head off.

32:57.105 --> 32:58.933
Sorry, I was just
trying to help.

32:58.977 --> 33:01.762
You didn't help.
You actually made things worse.

33:01.805 --> 33:03.285
Like always.

33:03.329 --> 33:06.071
Like always?It was hard enough
when you were just like

33:06.114 --> 33:07.289
a ghost haunting me.

33:07.333 --> 33:09.074
Now you're he-here...

33:09.117 --> 33:11.032
I didn't realize.You didn't realize

33:11.076 --> 33:13.600
that you leaving might have
actually affected me?

33:13.643 --> 33:15.123
It did.

33:15.167 --> 33:17.125
And now you're back. What do you
want? What do you want?

33:20.302 --> 33:22.391
You're right.

33:23.697 --> 33:25.786
I'm sorry.

33:25.829 --> 33:27.309
I'll leave you alone.

33:27.353 --> 33:29.094
I mean, it shouldn't be
too hard for you.

33:29.137 --> 33:31.792
You've had 18 years of practice.

33:34.490 --> 33:37.406
Imagine if it were always
like this.

33:37.450 --> 33:39.234
You're crazy.

33:39.278 --> 33:40.975
Am I?Mm-hmm.

33:41.019 --> 33:42.542
You're crazy if you think

33:42.585 --> 33:45.197
that I'm gonna live
in Town Hall with you.

33:45.240 --> 33:47.155
Okay, then where?

33:47.199 --> 33:48.461
Mm...

33:48.504 --> 33:50.376
♪ Any better now?

33:50.419 --> 33:53.118
Big house with a porch

33:53.161 --> 33:55.816
that wraps all the way around.

33:55.859 --> 33:58.906
And there should be water
right out front.

33:58.949 --> 34:00.125
Salt or fresh?

34:00.168 --> 34:02.692
Salt.

34:02.736 --> 34:05.086
And there should be
a little beach,

34:05.130 --> 34:06.653
for bonfires.

34:06.696 --> 34:11.092
Okay, salt, beach, bonfires.Mm-hmm.

34:11.136 --> 34:12.833
Anything else?

34:12.876 --> 34:15.401
There should be...

34:15.444 --> 34:19.144
a view of the sunset,
good schools.

34:19.187 --> 34:20.754
We've got a big house
on the ocean.

34:20.797 --> 34:22.843
You want to teach,
teach surfing.

34:22.886 --> 34:26.325
No, not for me; for Josh.

34:26.368 --> 34:30.111
♪ I can't forget the skin
pulled tight ♪

34:30.155 --> 34:31.808
♪ Every letter read...

34:31.852 --> 34:36.117
We could do this, you know.

34:36.161 --> 34:39.512
Find a way to be together

34:39.555 --> 34:43.342
without disrupting Josh's life
too much.

34:44.821 --> 34:46.823
It's not just Josh.

34:46.867 --> 34:48.347
What you're talking about
would affect

34:48.390 --> 34:49.957
everyone in our lives.

34:50.000 --> 34:52.873
Everyone we love would be caught
in the blast radius

34:52.916 --> 34:54.440
of that decision.

34:54.483 --> 34:57.138
I guess things are more
complicated now

34:57.182 --> 34:59.358
than when we were 17.

35:00.663 --> 35:02.709
♪

35:04.580 --> 35:06.843
♪ What only you can say...

35:06.887 --> 35:10.020
I can see that house
on the beach.

35:10.064 --> 35:11.761
Me, too.

35:11.805 --> 35:14.547
It's more real than
any dream I've ever had.

35:14.590 --> 35:16.984
♪ What only you can say...

35:17.027 --> 35:20.509
Yeah, but...

35:20.553 --> 35:22.120
it's still just a dream,

35:22.163 --> 35:27.168
and that's all
it can ever be.

35:27.212 --> 35:29.997
♪ We are ready for it

35:30.040 --> 35:32.260
I love you.

35:33.392 --> 35:34.697
I love you, too.

35:34.741 --> 35:36.656
♪ What only you can say

35:36.699 --> 35:38.571
♪ We are ready for it.

35:50.452 --> 35:52.541
Can I come in?

35:53.847 --> 35:55.805
It's your bedroom.

35:57.503 --> 35:59.766
[wind whistling outside]

36:11.995 --> 36:13.910
I'm so sorry.

36:13.954 --> 36:17.566
I had no right to behave
the way I did.

36:17.610 --> 36:20.352
It's just when you have
the dad that I have

36:20.395 --> 36:23.572
and the brother that I have,
you spend...

36:24.791 --> 36:27.750
...every second of every day
convinced that...

36:27.794 --> 36:29.535
Every man who comes
into your life

36:29.578 --> 36:32.712
is just looking for a way
to get back out again.

36:34.104 --> 36:35.758
It's not an excuse.

36:35.802 --> 36:39.545
I don't get to hurt you just
because someone else hurt me.

36:41.416 --> 36:43.462
The problem is I like you.

36:44.811 --> 36:46.378
A lot.

36:46.421 --> 36:49.207
When it looked like you were
lying, I-I got scared

36:49.250 --> 36:51.557
and I-I just tried
to push you away

36:51.600 --> 36:54.168
before you could push me away;
I'm so sorry.

36:54.212 --> 36:57.693
It looked like I was lying
because I was, Sarah.

36:57.737 --> 36:59.608
I told you I was going
to South Carolina

36:59.652 --> 37:01.480
for a story,
and that wasn't true.

37:01.523 --> 37:04.613
But you weren't wrong to
feel like something was off.

37:05.701 --> 37:08.269
Neither was your dad.

37:08.313 --> 37:09.792
So you're not upset?

37:09.836 --> 37:12.142
You have a bit of a temper, yes.

37:12.186 --> 37:14.928
That spark is--

37:14.971 --> 37:18.236
is part of what drew me
to you in the first place.

37:18.279 --> 37:20.325
See, the problem is

37:20.368 --> 37:22.892
I like you.

37:24.198 --> 37:25.678
A lot.

37:28.811 --> 37:31.684
I don't want to sit in
anyone's bathtub but yours.

37:31.727 --> 37:34.600
I don't want anyone else
in my bathtub.

37:35.949 --> 37:37.298
Okay.

37:37.342 --> 37:39.561
Okay? Okay.

37:42.347 --> 37:46.307
["Let It Go By"
by Fiora playing]

37:46.351 --> 37:48.744
♪

37:53.488 --> 37:56.839
♪ If you're not brave enough
to call ♪

37:59.929 --> 38:01.279
No, um...

38:01.322 --> 38:02.845
Sorry. Can't seem to stop
getting in your way here.

38:02.889 --> 38:06.066
Yeah, tell me about it.

38:08.373 --> 38:09.635
Listen, Sarah,

38:09.678 --> 38:11.941
let me get out of
your hair and then

38:11.985 --> 38:14.248
you won't see me again,
I promise.
Okay.

38:14.292 --> 38:17.556
I think that's a pretty
unrealistic promise to make

38:17.599 --> 38:19.732
in a town this size.

38:19.775 --> 38:20.950
Well, I will do my best.

38:20.994 --> 38:24.302
I do not want to
complicate your life.

38:24.345 --> 38:26.565
I think it's pretty clear that

38:26.608 --> 38:28.436
you've been complicating my life
for a while now.

38:28.480 --> 38:31.134
Well, so...[pours cereal]

38:31.178 --> 38:33.136
what-what do you suggest?

38:33.180 --> 38:34.747
I think we need to
set some boundaries,

38:34.790 --> 38:38.272
define the terms, you know,
starting with the "dad" thing.

38:38.316 --> 38:39.708
What dad thing?

38:39.752 --> 38:41.014
You don't have to avoid me,
but you also don't get

38:41.057 --> 38:42.581
to be my father.

38:42.624 --> 38:45.018
You abandoned that
responsibility

38:45.061 --> 38:46.889
a long time ago.

38:46.933 --> 38:50.240
Any relationship we
have moving forward

38:50.284 --> 38:52.852
starts with that.
Deal?

38:52.895 --> 38:56.551
Deal. And...

38:56.595 --> 38:57.770
thank you, Sarah.

38:57.813 --> 38:59.293
You're welcome, Paul.

38:59.337 --> 39:02.427
♪ Go by, let it go by

